    "content": "<p>Toluene reacts with mixed acid at $$25^{\\circ} \\mathrm{C}$$ to produce</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "nearly equal amounts of $$\\underline{o}$$- and $$\\underline{m}$$- nitrotoluene"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "$$\\underline{p}$$ only"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "predominantly $$\\underline{o}$$- nitrotoluene and $$\\underline{p}$$- nitrotoluene"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "2, 4, 6-trinitrotoluene (only)"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "C"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>Toluene, which is also known as methylbenzene, undergoes nitration when reacted with mixed acid, typically a mixture of concentrated nitric acid ($$\\mathrm{HNO_3}$$) and concentrated sulfuric acid ($$\\mathrm{H_2SO_4}$$). This reaction introduces a nitro group ($$\\mathrm{-NO_2}$$) onto the benzene ring of toluene. The methyl group ($$\\mathrm{-CH_3}$$) attached to the benzene ring is an electron-donating group (EDG) and it activates the ortho (2 and 6) and para (4) positions on the ring, making them more susceptible to electrophilic substitution reactions.</p>\n<img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/6y3zli1lx0t4le8/a3ed3904-a419-4e83-9cbf-33dcb718a459/a9f86df0-22aa-11ef-8d60-57a388b9654e/file-6y3zli1lx0t4le9.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/6y3zli1lx0t4le8/a3ed3904-a419-4e83-9cbf-33dcb718a459/a9f86df0-22aa-11ef-8d60-57a388b9654e/file-6y3zli1lx0t4le9.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"WB JEE 2024 Chemistry - Aromatic Chemistry Question 2 English Explanation\">\n<p>Among the given options, let's evaluate them in detail:</p>\n\n<p><strong>Option A:</strong> This suggests that toluene produces nearly equal amounts of $$\\underline{o}$$- nitrotoluene (ortho-nitrotoluene) and $$\\underline{m}$$- nitrotoluene (meta-nitrotoluene). However, because the methyl group is an activating and ortho/para-directing group, meta-nitrotoluene is produced in very minor amounts compared to ortho and para isomers.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Option B:</strong> This suggests that the reaction only produces $$\\underline{p}$$- nitrotoluene. While the para isomer is one of the products, it is not the only product. The ortho isomer is also formed in significant amounts.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Option C:</strong> This option suggests that the reaction predominately produces $$\\underline{o}$$- nitrotoluene and $$\\underline{p}$$- nitrotoluene. This is correct because the methyl group directs the nitration to the ortho and para positions on the benzene ring.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Option D:</strong> This suggests that the reaction produces 2, 4, 6-trinitrotoluene (TNT) only. This is not true at the given condition ($$25^{\\circ} \\mathrm{C}$$), as the formation of TNT requires more stringent conditions including higher temperature and multiple steps of nitration.</p>\n\n<p>Therefore, the correct answer is:</p>\n\n<p><strong>Option C:</strong> predominantly $$\\underline{o}$$- nitrotoluene and $$\\underline{p}$$- nitrotoluene</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2024,
    "yearKey": "wb-jee-2024",
    "difficulty": null
  },
